### Issue #8: Excessive Use of `any` Type (104 Occurrences)

- **Files**: Multiple files across `src/` directory
- **Category**: Type Safety / TypeScript
- **Description**: 104 uses of `any` type found throughout codebase, reducing type safety benefits
- **Impact**: Loss of compile-time type checking, potential runtime errors
- **High-frequency files**:
  - `src/web/server.ts`: 27 occurrences
  - `src/web/server.test.ts`: 20 occurrences
  - `src/services/icpDiscovery.ts`: 5 occurrences
  - `src/services/emailEvents.ts`: 7 occurrences
- **Fix**: Gradually replace `any` with proper types or `unknown` with type guards
- **Example Fix**:

```typescript
// BEFORE
const extractSources = (data: any) => {
  const items = data?.results ?? [];
  return items.map((it: any) => ({
    // ...
  }));
};

// AFTER
interface ExaResult {
  results?: Array<{
    url: string;
    title: string;
    // ...
  }>;
}

const extractSources = (data: ExaResult) => {
  const items = data?.results ?? [];
  return items.map((it) => ({
    // ...
  }));
};
```

### Issue #9: Error Objects with Dynamic Properties

- **Files**:
  - `src/services/emailOutbound.ts:194`
  - `src/services/campaigns.ts:78-79`
  - `src/status.ts:30-31`
- **Category**: Type Safety / Error Handling
- **Description**: Errors are augmented with custom properties using `any` cast: `(err as any).code = 'ERR_...'`
- **Impact**: Type-unsafe error handling, potential for runtime issues
- **Fix**: Create custom error classes instead of modifying Error objects

```typescript
// BEFORE
const err = new Error('Invalid status');
(err as any).code = 'ERR_STATUS_INVALID';
(err as any).details = { allowedStatuses };
throw err;

// AFTER
class StatusError extends Error {
  code: string;
  details?: Record<string, unknown>;

  constructor(message: string, code: string, details?: Record<string, unknown>) {
    super(message);
    this.code = code;
    this.details = details;
    this.name = 'StatusError';
  }
}

throw new StatusError('Invalid status', 'ERR_STATUS_INVALID', { allowedStatuses });
```

